if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['ent_p2_salivary']=[
  {q:"The largest salivary gland in the body is:",o:["Parotid gland","Minor salivary gland","Sublingual gland","Submandibular gland","Von Ebner gland"],a:0,e:"The parotid gland is the largest major salivary gland and lies below external acoustic meatus. Facial swelling develops clinically in inflammatory and neoplastic disorders.<br><br>It is predominantly serous in secretion and drains saliva into oral cavity through Stensen duct.<br><br>Sublingual gland (option C), minor salivary glands (option B), submandibular gland (option D), and Von Ebner glands (option E) are smaller structures.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The duct of parotid gland opens opposite the:",o:["Upper second molar tooth","Lower central incisor","Upper canine tooth","Lower first molar tooth","Upper first premolar tooth"],a:0,e:"Stensen duct of parotid gland opens into oral vestibule opposite upper second molar tooth. Pain during mastication develops clinically in duct obstruction.<br><br>The duct crosses masseter muscle before piercing buccinator to enter oral cavity.<br><br>Lower central incisor (option B), upper canine (option C), lower first molar (option D), and upper premolar (option E) are incorrect sites.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The facial nerve divides the parotid gland into:",o:["Deep and superficial lobes","Medial and lateral lobes","Superior and inferior lobes","Anterior and posterior lobes","Right and left segments"],a:0,e:"The facial nerve traverses parotid gland and divides it into superficial and deep lobes. Facial weakness develops clinically after nerve injury during surgery.<br><br>This anatomical relationship is surgically important during parotidectomy procedures.<br><br>Superior and inferior lobes (option C), medial and lateral lobes (option B), anterior and posterior lobes (option D), and right-left segments (option E) are incorrect divisions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The salivary gland most commonly affected by calculi is:",o:["Parotid gland","Sublingual gland","Minor salivary gland","Lacrimal gland","Submandibular gland"],a:4,e:"Submandibular gland is most commonly affected by salivary calculi because of viscous alkaline secretions. Pain during meals develops clinically in duct obstruction.<br><br>Its long upward-running duct also predisposes to salivary stasis and stone formation.<br><br>Parotid gland (option A), sublingual gland (option B), minor salivary glands (option C), and lacrimal gland (option D) are less commonly involved.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The parasympathetic secretomotor supply of parotid gland is derived from the:",o:["Facial nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Accessory nerve"],a:1,e:"Parasympathetic secretomotor fibers to parotid gland originate from glossopharyngeal nerve. Reduced salivary secretion develops clinically after autonomic interruption.<br><br>Fibers pass through lesser petrosal nerve and otic ganglion before reaching auriculotemporal nerve.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option C), vagus nerve (option D), and accessory nerve (option E) are unrelated pathways.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"Wharton duct drains the:",o:["Parotid gland","Lacrimal gland","Sublingual gland only","Submandibular gland","Minor salivary glands"],a:3,e:"Wharton duct drains submandibular gland into floor of mouth near lingual frenulum. Painful swelling develops clinically when duct becomes obstructed.<br><br>The duct passes forward between mylohyoid and hyoglossus muscles before opening orally.<br><br>Parotid gland (option A), lacrimal gland (option B), sublingual gland only (option C), and minor salivary glands (option E) use different ducts.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The salivary gland with predominantly mucous secretion is:",o:["Sublingual gland","Von Ebner gland","Parotid gland","Parathyroid gland","Lacrimal gland"],a:0,e:"The sublingual gland predominantly produces mucous secretions important for oral lubrication. Dryness develops clinically if secretion decreases significantly.<br><br>In contrast, parotid gland mainly produces serous watery saliva.<br><br>Parotid gland (option C), Von Ebner gland (option B), parathyroid gland (option D), and lacrimal gland (option E) have different secretory functions.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"The nerve closely related to submandibular duct is the:",o:["Facial nerve","Lingual nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Vagus nerve","Phrenic nerve"],a:1,e:"The lingual nerve loops around submandibular duct in floor of mouth. Tongue numbness develops clinically after accidental injury during surgery.<br><br>This close anatomical relation becomes important during submandibular gland excision procedures.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), glossopharyngeal nerve (option C), vagus nerve (option D), and phrenic nerve (option E) are less closely related.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The duct of sublingual gland is called:",o:["Rivinus duct","Stensen duct","Wharton duct","Bartholin duct","Santorini duct"],a:0,e:"Sublingual gland drains mainly through multiple small ducts called ducts of Rivinus. Oral floor swelling develops clinically if drainage becomes obstructed.<br><br>Some ducts may unite to form a larger Bartholin duct opening near Wharton duct.<br><br>Stensen duct (option B), Wharton duct (option C), Bartholin duct (option D), and Santorini duct (option E) are different ducts.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The main blood supply of parotid gland is from the:",o:["Facial artery","Maxillary artery only","External carotid artery","Internal carotid artery","Lingual artery"],a:2,e:"The external carotid artery passes through parotid gland and provides major arterial supply. Bleeding develops clinically if vascular injury occurs during parotid surgery.<br><br>Within gland substance, the artery divides into terminal branches including superficial temporal artery.<br><br>Facial artery (option A), maxillary artery alone (option B), internal carotid artery (option D), and lingual artery (option E) are less important sources.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The salivary gland contributing most resting saliva is:",o:["Parotid gland","Sublingual gland","Minor salivary glands","Submandibular gland","Von Ebner gland"],a:3,e:"Submandibular gland contributes most resting saliva in unstimulated conditions. Xerostomia develops clinically if secretion decreases significantly.<br><br>Its mixed seromucous secretion maintains baseline oral lubrication and digestion.<br><br>Parotid gland (option A), sublingual gland (option B), minor glands (option C), and Von Ebner glands (option E) contribute smaller amounts.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"The facial nerve exits skull through the:",o:["Stylomastoid foramen","Foramen ovale","Jugular foramen","Foramen spinosum","Hypoglossal canal"],a:0,e:"The facial nerve exits the skull through stylomastoid foramen before entering parotid gland. Facial paralysis develops clinically after injury along this course.<br><br>Within parotid gland, it divides into terminal branches supplying muscles of facial expression.<br><br>Jugular foramen (option C), foramen ovale (option B), foramen spinosum (option D), and hypoglossal canal (option E) transmit other nerves.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The saliva of parotid gland is mainly:",o:["Mucous","Serous","Mixed equally","Sebaceous","Keratinous"],a:1,e:"Parotid gland predominantly secretes serous watery saliva rich in digestive enzymes. Increased secretion develops clinically during mastication and gustatory stimulation.<br><br>Amylase within parotid saliva initiates carbohydrate digestion in oral cavity.<br><br>Mucous secretion (option A), equal mixed secretion (option C), sebaceous secretion (option D), and keratinous secretion (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"The salivary gland lying within submandibular triangle is the:",o:["Sublingual gland","Parotid gland","Lacrimal gland","Submandibular gland","Pituitary gland"],a:3,e:"The submandibular gland lies within submandibular triangle beneath body of mandible. Swelling develops clinically below mandibular margin in inflammatory disease.<br><br>It wraps around posterior border of mylohyoid muscle into floor of mouth.<br><br>Sublingual gland (option A), parotid gland (option B), lacrimal gland (option C), and pituitary gland (option E) occupy different locations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The main function of saliva in digestion is initiation of digestion of:",o:["Carbohydrates","Lipids","Proteins","Vitamins","Minerals"],a:0,e:"Saliva initiates carbohydrate digestion through salivary amylase secretion. Difficulty swallowing dry food develops clinically in xerostomia states.<br><br>The enzyme begins starch breakdown within oral cavity before gastric digestion continues.<br><br>Proteins (option C), lipids (option B), vitamins (option D), and minerals (option E) are less significantly affected initially.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"The structure passing superficially over parotid duct is the:",o:["Buccal branch of facial nerve","Facial vein","Facial artery","Hypoglossal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve"],a:0,e:"Buccal branches of facial nerve run superficially across parotid duct over masseter muscle. Facial asymmetry develops clinically after accidental nerve damage.<br><br>This relation is important during parotid surgery and facial trauma repair.<br><br>Facial artery (option C), facial vein (option B), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and glossopharyngeal nerve (option E) follow different pathways.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The saliva becomes hypotonic mainly because of reabsorption of:",o:["Sodium","Calcium","Potassium","Bicarbonate","Glucose"],a:0,e:"Salivary ducts reabsorb sodium actively, making final saliva hypotonic relative to plasma. Electrolyte imbalance develops clinically in severe salivary dysfunction states.<br><br>Potassium and bicarbonate are simultaneously secreted into ductal saliva.<br><br>Calcium (option B), potassium (option C), bicarbonate (option D), and glucose (option E) are less responsible for hypotonicity.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"The salivary gland located in floor of mouth above mylohyoid muscle is:",o:["Parotid gland","Lacrimal gland","Sublingual gland","Submandibular gland","Thyroid gland"],a:2,e:"The sublingual gland lies in floor of mouth above mylohyoid muscle beneath mucosa. Ranula formation develops clinically after duct obstruction.<br><br>It forms the sublingual fold on either side of tongue base.<br><br>Parotid gland (option A), lacrimal gland (option B), submandibular gland (option D), and thyroid gland (option E) occupy different regions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The parasympathetic supply to submandibular gland is carried by the:",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Chorda tympani nerve","Vagus nerve","Phrenic nerve","Greater petrosal nerve"],a:1,e:"Parasympathetic fibers to submandibular gland travel through chorda tympani branch of facial nerve. Reduced salivation develops clinically after autonomic interruption.<br><br>Fibers synapse within submandibular ganglion before supplying salivary tissue.<br><br>Glossopharyngeal nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option C), phrenic nerve (option D), and greater petrosal nerve (option E) supply different structures.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The salivary gland most commonly involved in mumps is the:",o:["Sublingual gland","Minor salivary gland","Submandibular gland","Parotid gland","Lacrimal gland"],a:3,e:"Mumps classically produces painful enlargement of parotid glands bilaterally. Fever and painful mastication develop clinically during acute viral infection.<br><br>The virus shows strong affinity for glandular tissue, particularly the parotid salivary gland.<br><br>Sublingual gland (option A), minor salivary glands (option B), submandibular gland (option C), and lacrimal gland (option E) are less commonly affected.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 46-year-old man develops weakness of forehead wrinkling and inability to close the eye after superficial parotidectomy. The injured structure is most likely the:",o:["Facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Lingual nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Auriculotemporal nerve"],a:0,e:"The facial nerve traverses parotid gland and remains highly vulnerable during parotid surgery. Facial asymmetry develops clinically after injury to its terminal branches.<br><br>Superficial parotidectomy requires careful identification and preservation of the nerve trunk and divisions.<br><br>Lingual nerve (option C), hypoglossal nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and auriculotemporal nerve (option E) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient presents with painful swelling below mandible that worsens during meals. Examination reveals stone in floor of mouth near duct opening. The involved gland is:",o:["Parotid gland","Sublingual gland","Minor salivary gland","Submandibular gland","Lacrimal gland"],a:3,e:"Submandibular calculi commonly produce painful swelling that increases during salivary stimulation at mealtimes. Salivary stasis develops clinically because of duct obstruction.<br><br>Wharton duct is long and saliva from this gland is relatively viscous and alkaline.<br><br>Parotid gland (option A), sublingual gland (option B), minor glands (option C), and lacrimal gland (option E) are less commonly affected.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"During excision of submandibular gland, injury to lingual nerve would most likely produce:",o:["Facial paralysis","Loss of taste anterior tongue","Hoarseness","Dysphagia only","Shoulder drooping"],a:1,e:"Lingual nerve carries general sensation while chorda tympani fibers convey taste from anterior tongue. Tongue numbness develops clinically after surgical injury.<br><br>The nerve loops around Wharton duct and remains closely related during gland excision.<br><br>Facial paralysis (option A), hoarseness (option C), isolated dysphagia (option D), and shoulder drooping (option E) indicate different nerve injuries.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 28-year-old patient develops translucent bluish swelling in floor of mouth after trauma to sublingual region. The diagnosis is:",o:["Branchial cyst","Thyroglossal cyst","Ranula","Dermoid cyst","Sialadenitis"],a:2,e:"Ranula is a mucous retention cyst arising commonly from sublingual gland duct obstruction. Floor-of-mouth swelling develops clinically with bluish translucent appearance.<br><br>Extravasation of saliva into surrounding tissues produces characteristic cystic lesion formation.<br><br>Branchial cyst (option A), thyroglossal cyst (option B), dermoid cyst (option D), and sialadenitis (option E) present differently.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent parotid swelling during meals undergoes sialography. The investigation primarily evaluates:",o:["Salivary duct system","Facial nerve function","Thyroid hormone levels","Vocal cord mobility","Mastoid air cells"],a:0,e:"Sialography outlines salivary duct architecture and helps identify obstruction or ductal abnormalities. Painful gland enlargement develops clinically during salivary stimulation.<br><br>Contrast injection demonstrates strictures, calculi, and chronic inflammatory ductal changes effectively.<br><br>Facial nerve function (option B), thyroid hormones (option C), vocal cord mobility (option D), and mastoid air cells (option E) are unrelated assessments.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops gustatory sweating over parotid region after parotidectomy. The condition is called:",o:["Horner syndrome","Bell palsy","Frey syndrome","Heerfordt syndrome","Mikulicz disease"],a:2,e:"Frey syndrome occurs because regenerating parasympathetic fibers aberrantly innervate sweat glands after parotid surgery. Sweating develops clinically during eating or salivary stimulation.<br><br>The auriculotemporal nerve pathway is commonly involved in this postoperative complication.<br><br>Horner syndrome (option A), Bell palsy (option B), Heerfordt syndrome (option D), and Mikulicz disease (option E) are different disorders.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with xerostomia after radiotherapy is most likely to have damage predominantly affecting the:",o:["Facial artery","Serous acini","Thyroid follicles","Vocal cords","Mastoid cells"],a:1,e:"Radiotherapy commonly damages serous acinar cells of salivary glands causing xerostomia. Difficulty swallowing dry food develops clinically after reduced saliva production.<br><br>Parotid glands are especially radiosensitive because of predominantly serous secretory tissue.<br><br>Facial artery (option A), thyroid follicles (option C), vocal cords (option D), and mastoid cells (option E) are less directly affected.<br><br><em>(Guyton and Hall Physiology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with bilateral painful parotid swelling, fever, and difficulty chewing. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Acute bacterial sialadenitis","Ranula","Mumps","Pleomorphic adenoma","Sjögren syndrome"],a:2,e:"Mumps is a viral infection classically affecting parotid glands bilaterally in children. Pain during mastication develops clinically because of glandular inflammation.<br><br>The paramyxovirus demonstrates affinity for salivary gland tissue, especially parotid gland.<br><br>Acute bacterial sialadenitis (option A), ranula (option B), pleomorphic adenoma (option D), and Sjögren syndrome (option E) present differently.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"During removal of deep lobe parotid tumor, the surgeon must be especially careful about the:",o:["Hypoglossal nerve","Facial nerve trunk","Vagus nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Phrenic nerve"],a:1,e:"Deep lobe parotid tumors remain closely related to facial nerve trunk and branches. Permanent facial weakness develops clinically after extensive nerve injury.<br><br>Identification of the main trunk at stylomastoid foramen is an essential surgical step.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option C), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and phrenic nerve (option E) are less closely related.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with submandibular sialolithiasis undergoes gland excision. Which structure is most at risk during surgery?",o:["Internal jugular vein","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Lingual nerve","Accessory nerve","Superior thyroid artery"],a:2,e:"The lingual nerve passes in close relation to Wharton duct and submandibular gland. Altered tongue sensation develops clinically after surgical trauma.<br><br>Careful dissection within floor of mouth region helps prevent sensory and taste disturbances.<br><br>Internal jugular vein (option A), recurrent laryngeal nerve (option B), accessory nerve (option D), and superior thyroid artery (option E) are less vulnerable here.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old diabetic man presents with painful parotid swelling, fever, trismus, and purulent discharge from Stensen duct. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Acute suppurative parotitis","Ranula","Sjögren syndrome","Branchial cyst"],a:1,e:"Acute suppurative parotitis commonly affects dehydrated or diabetic elderly patients. Fever and painful gland enlargement develop clinically with purulent duct discharge.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus is the usual pathogen and ascending infection occurs through Stensen duct.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (option A), ranula (option C), Sjögren syndrome (option D), and branchial cyst (option E) are less acute presentations.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute bacterial parotitis is initially managed with:",o:["Intravenous antibiotics and hydration","Radioiodine therapy","Immediate parotidectomy","Hemithyroidectomy","Observation only"],a:0,e:"Acute bacterial parotitis requires prompt antibiotic therapy and adequate hydration. Fever and severe gland tenderness develop clinically because of bacterial inflammation.<br><br>Improved salivary flow helps reduce ascending ductal infection and prevents abscess formation.<br><br>Immediate parotidectomy (option C), radioiodine therapy (option B), thyroid surgery (option D), and observation (option E) are inappropriate measures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 42-year-old woman presents with recurrent painful swelling of submandibular gland during meals. CT scan reveals ductal calculus. The definitive management is:",o:["Radiotherapy","Chemotherapy","Sialendoscopy or stone removal","Observation only","Corticosteroids alone"],a:2,e:"Submandibular sialolithiasis commonly causes meal-related painful swelling because of duct obstruction. Recurrent infection develops clinically if obstruction persists.<br><br>Definitive treatment involves duct exploration, sialendoscopy, or gland excision depending on stone location.<br><br>Radiotherapy (option A), chemotherapy (option B), observation (option D), and steroids (option E) do not correct obstruction.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest organism causing acute suppurative parotitis is:",o:["Staphylococcus aureus","Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Streptococcus pyogenes","Candida albicans","Pseudomonas aeruginosa"],a:0,e:"Staphylococcus aureus is the commonest pathogen responsible for acute suppurative parotitis. Purulent duct discharge develops clinically in severe gland infection.<br><br>Ascending oral cavity infection commonly occurs when salivary flow decreases significantly.<br><br>Streptococcus pyogenes (option C), tuberculosis (option B), Candida (option D), and Pseudomonas (option E) are less frequent causes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A postoperative elderly patient develops painful parotid swelling with fever and dehydration. The major predisposing factor is:",o:["Hypercalcemia","Excess salivation","Hyperthyroidism","Xerostomia and stasis","Vocal abuse"],a:3,e:"Postoperative dehydration reduces salivary flow and predisposes to ascending bacterial parotid infection. Painful swelling develops clinically with fever and trismus.<br><br>Salivary stasis permits bacterial multiplication within Stensen duct and gland tissue.<br><br>Hypercalcemia (option A), excess salivation (option B), hyperthyroidism (option C), and vocal abuse (option E) are less relevant factors.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 12-year-old boy develops bilateral parotid swelling, fever, and orchitis. The causative organism is:",o:["Paramyxovirus","Epstein-Barr virus","Cytomegalovirus","Herpes simplex virus","Adenovirus"],a:0,e:"Mumps is caused by paramyxovirus and commonly affects parotid glands bilaterally. Orchitis develops clinically as an important complication in postpubertal males.<br><br>The virus spreads through respiratory droplets and targets glandular tissues preferentially.<br><br>Epstein-Barr virus (option B), cytomegalovirus (option C), herpes simplex virus (option D), and adenovirus (option E) are less typical causes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute suppurative parotitis develops fluctuant swelling despite antibiotics. The next management step is:",o:["Observation only","Oral steroids","Thyroidectomy","Surgical drainage","Radioiodine therapy"],a:3,e:"Parotid abscess formation requires surgical drainage when fluctuation develops despite antibiotic therapy. Fever and severe tenderness persist clinically in abscess formation.<br><br>Incision and drainage prevent further spread of infection and tissue destruction.<br><br>Observation (option A), oral steroids (option B), thyroidectomy (option C), and radioiodine therapy (option E) are inappropriate interventions.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 50-year-old patient presents with dry mouth, dry eyes, and recurrent bilateral parotid enlargement. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Acute bacterial parotitis","Ranula","Sjögren syndrome","Pleomorphic adenoma","Branchial cyst"],a:2,e:"Sjögren syndrome is an autoimmune disorder involving salivary and lacrimal gland destruction. Xerostomia and keratoconjunctivitis sicca develop clinically prominently.<br><br>Chronic lymphocytic infiltration leads to recurrent gland enlargement and reduced secretions.<br><br>Acute bacterial parotitis (option A), ranula (option B), pleomorphic adenoma (option D), and branchial cyst (option E) present differently.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent submandibular gland infection undergoes gland excision. The nerve most at risk during surgery is:",o:["Facial nerve trunk","Vagus nerve","Lingual nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Phrenic nerve"],a:2,e:"The lingual nerve loops around Wharton duct and remains vulnerable during submandibular gland surgery. Tongue numbness develops clinically after accidental injury.<br><br>Taste disturbance may also occur because chorda tympani fibers accompany the nerve.<br><br>Facial nerve trunk (option A), vagus nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and phrenic nerve (option E) are less closely related.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The salivary gland least commonly affected by calculi is:",o:["Submandibular gland","Parotid gland","Minor salivary glands","Sublingual gland","Thyroid gland"],a:3,e:"Sublingual gland is rarely affected by calculi because of multiple short ducts and relatively free drainage. Obstructive swelling develops clinically far less frequently.<br><br>Submandibular gland remains most commonly affected because of viscous saliva and duct anatomy.<br><br>Submandibular gland (option A), parotid gland (option B), minor glands (option C), and thyroid gland (option E) are less appropriate choices.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A diabetic elderly patient presents with parotid abscess extending into deep neck spaces. The most feared complication is:",o:["Otitis externa","Mediastinitis","Cataract formation","Bell palsy","Nasal obstruction"],a:1,e:"Deep neck extension of salivary infection may descend through fascial planes into mediastinum. Septic shock develops clinically in advanced mediastinitis.<br><br>Aggressive intravenous antibiotics and surgical drainage become essential emergency measures.<br><br>Otitis externa (option A), cataract formation (option C), Bell palsy (option D), and nasal obstruction (option E) are less dangerous complications.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 30-year-old woman develops recurrent painful swelling below mandible that subsides after meals. Examination suggests partial duct obstruction without stone. Initial management includes:",o:["Immediate gland excision","Thyroidectomy","Radical neck dissection","Chemotherapy","Sialogogues and hydration"],a:4,e:"Partial salivary duct obstruction may improve with conservative measures increasing salivary flow. Meal-related swelling develops clinically because of transient duct blockage.<br><br>Hydration, gland massage, and sialogogues help flush retained secretions effectively.<br><br>Immediate excision (option A), neck dissection (option C), chemotherapy (option D), and thyroidectomy (option B) are unnecessary initially.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with HIV develops painless bilateral parotid enlargement due to lymphoepithelial cysts. The underlying pathology mainly involves:",o:["Acute bacterial infection","Autoimmune fibrosis","Salivary calculi","Lymphoid proliferation","Tuberculous granulomas"],a:3,e:"HIV-associated salivary gland disease commonly produces benign lymphoepithelial cyst formation. Bilateral parotid enlargement develops clinically without severe pain.<br><br>Reactive lymphoid proliferation within gland tissue contributes significantly to cyst development.<br><br>Acute bacterial infection (option A), autoimmune fibrosis (option B), calculi (option C), and tuberculosis (option E) are less typical mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe trismus and facial swelling after untreated parotid infection. The abscess most likely spread into the:",o:["Retropharyngeal space","Masticator space","Submental space","Danger space","Prevertebral space"],a:1,e:"Parotid infections may spread into adjacent masticator space causing severe trismus. Facial pain develops clinically because of muscle involvement and inflammation.<br><br>Close anatomical relation between parotid fascia and masticatory compartments facilitates extension.<br><br>Retropharyngeal space (option A), submental space (option C), danger space (option D), and prevertebral space (option E) are less direct extensions.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic recurrent parotitis undergoes imaging to evaluate ductal strictures. The most useful investigation is:",o:["Tympanometry","PET scan","Bronchoscopy","Sialography","Audiometry"],a:3,e:"Sialography outlines salivary duct anatomy and demonstrates strictures or chronic inflammatory changes. Recurrent painful swelling develops clinically during salivary stimulation.<br><br>Contrast imaging remains useful in evaluating recurrent obstructive salivary disorders.<br><br>Tympanometry (option A), PET scan (option B), bronchoscopy (option C), and audiometry (option E) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 9-year-old boy presents with painful parotid swelling and fever. Which complication of mumps is most likely after puberty?",o:["Osteomyelitis","Appendicitis","Glomerulonephritis","Retinal detachment","Orchitis"],a:4,e:"Orchitis is a well-recognized complication of mumps in postpubertal males. Testicular pain and swelling develop clinically several days after parotitis.<br><br>Although infertility is uncommon, severe bilateral involvement may impair fertility.<br><br>Osteomyelitis (option A), glomerulonephritis (option C), retinal detachment (option D), and appendicitis (option B) are less characteristic complications.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent submandibular sialadenitis has a stone located proximally within gland substance. Preferred management is:",o:["Oral antibiotics only","Duct massage alone","Submandibular gland excision","Observation indefinitely","Radiation therapy"],a:2,e:"Proximal intraglandular stones causing recurrent infection often require gland excision. Recurrent painful swelling develops clinically because obstruction persists chronically.<br><br>Deep hilar calculi are difficult to remove safely through simple duct exploration.<br><br>Antibiotics alone (option A), massage (option B), observation (option D), and radiation therapy (option E) are inadequate definitive treatments.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute parotitis develops facial weakness. This finding should raise suspicion of:",o:["Viral resolution","Benign obstruction","Nutritional deficiency","Malignancy or severe invasive infection","Dental caries only"],a:3,e:"Facial nerve palsy associated with parotid swelling is an ominous clinical sign. Progressive weakness develops clinically with malignant infiltration or severe destructive infection.<br><br>Benign inflammatory conditions rarely produce facial nerve dysfunction.<br><br>Viral resolution (option A), benign obstruction (option B), nutritional deficiency (option C), and dental caries (option E) are less likely explanations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A dehydrated ICU patient develops unilateral painful parotid enlargement with pus expressed from duct. The most appropriate immediate antibiotic coverage should target:",o:["Anaerobes only","Fungal organisms only","Tuberculosis exclusively","Staphylococcal infection","Viral pathogens only"],a:3,e:"Staphylococcus aureus remains the commonest pathogen causing acute suppurative parotitis in debilitated patients. Fever and gland tenderness develop clinically rapidly.<br><br>Empirical antibiotics should therefore include effective anti-staphylococcal coverage alongside hydration measures.<br><br>Anaerobes only (option A), fungi (option B), tuberculosis (option C), and viruses (option E) are less common causes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Sjögren syndrome is at increased risk of developing:",o:["Papillary thyroid carcinoma","Salivary gland lymphoma","Cholesteatoma","Acoustic neuroma","Pituitary adenoma"],a:1,e:"Chronic autoimmune lymphocytic infiltration in Sjögren syndrome predisposes to salivary gland lymphoma formation. Persistent gland enlargement develops clinically despite treatment.<br><br>Long-standing stimulation of B lymphocytes contributes to malignant transformation risk.<br><br>Papillary thyroid carcinoma (option A), cholesteatoma (option C), acoustic neuroma (option D), and pituitary adenoma (option E) show weaker associations.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoes superficial parotidectomy for chronic recurrent parotitis. The most important structure to identify and preserve during surgery is:",o:["Lingual nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Facial nerve","Vagus nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve"],a:2,e:"The facial nerve traverses parotid gland and is the most critical structure during parotid surgery. Facial asymmetry develops clinically after accidental nerve injury.<br><br>Identification of the main trunk near stylomastoid foramen minimizes postoperative functional complications.<br><br>Lingual nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option B), vagus nerve (option D), and glossopharyngeal nerve (option E) are less directly related.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops sweating and flushing over parotid region while eating after parotidectomy. The preferred treatment for persistent symptoms is:",o:["Oral antibiotics","Intravenous calcium","Total laryngectomy","Botulinum toxin injection","Radioiodine therapy"],a:3,e:"Frey syndrome results from aberrant parasympathetic regeneration after parotid surgery. Gustatory sweating develops clinically during meals or salivary stimulation.<br><br>Botulinum toxin effectively reduces sweating by blocking cholinergic stimulation of sweat glands.<br><br>Oral antibiotics (option A), calcium infusion (option B), laryngectomy (option C), and radioiodine therapy (option E) are inappropriate treatments.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with acute suppurative parotitis fails conservative treatment and develops abscess formation. Surgical drainage should be performed using:",o:["Midline neck incision","Posterior pharyngeal incision","Kocher collar incision","Transoral incision only","Modified Blair incision"],a:4,e:"Parotid abscess drainage is commonly performed through modified Blair incision to ensure adequate exposure. Persistent fever and fluctuation develop clinically in abscess formation.<br><br>This approach permits safe drainage while minimizing risk to facial nerve branches.<br><br>Midline neck incision (option A), Kocher incision (option C), transoral drainage (option D), and posterior pharyngeal incision (option B) are less suitable.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent submandibular sialolithiasis undergoes gland excision. Injury to which nerve may produce altered taste sensation?",o:["Vagus nerve","Accessory nerve","Phrenic nerve","Lingual nerve with chorda tympani fibers","Recurrent laryngeal nerve"],a:3,e:"The lingual nerve carries chorda tympani taste fibers supplying anterior tongue sensation. Taste disturbance develops clinically after surgical trauma during gland excision.<br><br>Its close relationship with Wharton duct makes careful dissection essential intraoperatively.<br><br>Vagus nerve (option A), accessory nerve (option B), phrenic nerve (option C), and recurrent laryngeal nerve (option E) serve different functions.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic xerostomia secondary to Sjögren syndrome is advised supportive management primarily including:",o:["Sialogogues and artificial saliva","Radical parotidectomy","Radiotherapy","Thyroid suppression therapy","Neck dissection"],a:0,e:"Supportive management in Sjögren syndrome aims to improve oral lubrication and reduce complications. Difficulty swallowing and dental caries develop clinically due to persistent dryness.<br><br>Artificial saliva and sialogogues enhance comfort and preserve oral health effectively.<br><br>Radical parotidectomy (option B), radiotherapy (option C), thyroid suppression (option D), and neck dissection (option E) are inappropriate routine treatments.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops complete facial paralysis after total parotidectomy. The most likely indication for sacrificing facial nerve during surgery was:",o:["Benign pleomorphic adenoma","Acute viral parotitis","Ranula formation","Malignant invasive tumor","Salivary fistula"],a:3,e:"Facial nerve sacrifice may become necessary when malignant parotid tumors directly infiltrate neural tissue. Progressive facial weakness develops clinically before surgery in advanced disease.<br><br>Complete tumor clearance sometimes requires nerve resection for oncological safety.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (option A), viral parotitis (option B), ranula (option C), and salivary fistula (option E) rarely require nerve sacrifice.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing sialendoscopy for salivary duct stone benefits mainly because the procedure is:",o:["Highly invasive","Organ-preserving and minimally invasive","Associated with mandatory gland excision","Performed without visualization","Used only for malignancy"],a:1,e:"Sialendoscopy permits minimally invasive management of obstructive salivary disorders while preserving gland function. Meal-related swelling develops clinically from duct obstruction.<br><br>Endoscopic visualization allows stone retrieval and ductal dilation without major surgery.<br><br>Highly invasive procedures (option A), mandatory excision (option C), blind instrumentation (option D), and exclusive malignancy use (option E) are incorrect statements.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Following submandibular gland excision, weakness of lower lip depression indicates injury to the:",o:["Marginal mandibular branch of facial nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Vagus nerve","Auriculotemporal nerve"],a:0,e:"The marginal mandibular branch of facial nerve is vulnerable during submandibular surgery. Lower lip asymmetry develops clinically during smiling or speaking.<br><br>Careful elevation of skin flaps below mandibular margin helps preserve this nerve branch.<br><br>Hypoglossal nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve (option C), vagus nerve (option D), and auriculotemporal nerve (option E) control different functions.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent bacterial sialadenitis is advised gland massage and hydration because these measures primarily:",o:["Destroy malignant cells","Reduce salivary flow","Improve salivary drainage","Suppress facial nerve function","Produce fibrosis"],a:2,e:"Hydration and gland massage improve salivary flow and reduce ductal stasis in recurrent sialadenitis. Painful gland swelling develops clinically during obstruction and infection.<br><br>Improved drainage decreases bacterial colonization and retained secretions within ducts.<br><br>Malignant cell destruction (option A), salivary reduction (option B), facial nerve suppression (option D), and fibrosis production (option E) are incorrect effects.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent parotid abscess develops persistent salivary leakage through skin after drainage. The complication is called:",o:["Ranula","Salivary fistula","Branchial sinus","Thyroglossal fistula","Pharyngocutaneous fistula"],a:1,e:"Salivary fistula represents abnormal communication allowing saliva to discharge externally through skin. Persistent watery leakage develops clinically during eating or salivary stimulation.<br><br>The condition may follow surgery, trauma, or abscess drainage involving salivary ducts.<br><br>Ranula (option A), branchial sinus (option C), thyroglossal fistula (option D), and pharyngocutaneous fistula (option E) are unrelated lesions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common benign tumor of salivary glands is:",o:["Warthin tumor","Mucoepidermoid carcinoma","Acinic cell carcinoma","Adenoid cystic carcinoma","Pleomorphic adenoma"],a:4,e:"Pleomorphic adenoma is the commonest benign salivary gland tumor, especially affecting parotid gland. Slow painless swelling develops clinically over several years.<br><br>The tumor contains both epithelial and mesenchymal stromal elements microscopically.<br><br>Warthin tumor (option A), mucoepidermoid carcinoma (option B), adenoid cystic carcinoma (option D), and acinic cell carcinoma (option C) are less common benign lesions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The salivary gland most commonly affected by tumors is the:",o:["Sublingual gland","Minor salivary glands","Lacrimal gland","Submandibular gland","Parotid gland"],a:4,e:"Parotid gland is the commonest site for salivary gland tumors overall. Painless gradually enlarging swelling develops clinically in most benign lesions.<br><br>Approximately eighty percent of salivary gland tumors arise within parotid tissue.<br><br>Sublingual gland (option A), minor salivary glands (option B), submandibular gland (option D), and lacrimal gland (option C) are less commonly involved.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parotid swelling develops facial nerve palsy. This finding strongly suggests:",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Benign cyst","Malignancy","Ranula","Sialolithiasis"],a:2,e:"Facial nerve palsy associated with parotid swelling strongly suggests malignant infiltration. Progressive facial weakness develops clinically because of neural invasion.<br><br>Benign salivary tumors rarely involve facial nerve directly.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (option A), benign cyst (option B), ranula (option D), and sialolithiasis (option E) usually spare facial nerve function.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common malignant salivary gland tumor is:",o:["Warthin tumor","Pleomorphic adenoma","Oncocytoma","Basal cell adenoma","Mucoepidermoid carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Mucoepidermoid carcinoma is the commonest malignant salivary gland neoplasm. Pain and facial weakness develop clinically in high-grade aggressive tumors.<br><br>The tumor contains varying proportions of mucous and squamous-type cells histologically.<br><br>Warthin tumor (option A), pleomorphic adenoma (option B), basal cell adenoma (option D), and oncocytoma (option C) are benign lesions.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 52-year-old smoker presents with cystic parotid swelling. Histology shows papillary cystic spaces lined by oncocytic epithelium with lymphoid stroma. The diagnosis is:",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Warthin tumor","Mucoepidermoid carcinoma","Acinic cell carcinoma","Adenoid cystic carcinoma"],a:1,e:"Warthin tumor commonly affects older male smokers and usually arises in parotid gland. Slow painless cystic swelling develops clinically over prolonged duration.<br><br>Histologically, it contains oncocytic epithelium with prominent lymphoid stroma.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (option A), mucoepidermoid carcinoma (option C), acinic cell carcinoma (option D), and adenoid cystic carcinoma (option E) differ microscopically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The preferred treatment for pleomorphic adenoma of parotid gland is:",o:["Radiotherapy only","Enucleation alone","Superficial parotidectomy","Chemotherapy","Observation only"],a:2,e:"Pleomorphic adenoma requires superficial parotidectomy with facial nerve preservation. Recurrence develops clinically after inadequate simple enucleation.<br><br>Microscopic pseudopod extensions beyond tumor capsule predispose to incomplete removal.<br><br>Radiotherapy (option A), enucleation alone (option B), chemotherapy (option D), and observation (option E) are inappropriate definitive treatments.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops gustatory sweating after parotid surgery. The complication is called:",o:["Bell palsy","Ramsay Hunt syndrome","Horner syndrome","Heerfordt syndrome","Frey syndrome"],a:4,e:"Frey syndrome results from aberrant regeneration of parasympathetic fibers after parotid surgery. Sweating develops clinically during eating or salivary stimulation.<br><br>The condition commonly affects skin overlying parotid operative site.<br><br>Bell palsy (option A), Horner syndrome (option C), Heerfordt syndrome (option D), and Ramsay Hunt syndrome (option B) are unrelated disorders.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A slowly enlarging painless palatal mass is most likely arising from:",o:["Thyroid gland","Minor salivary glands","Sublingual gland only","Lacrimal gland","Pituitary gland"],a:1,e:"Minor salivary gland tumors commonly arise on palate because of abundant gland distribution there. Ulceration develops clinically in malignant lesions later.<br><br>Both benign and malignant salivary neoplasms may occur within palatal mucosa.<br><br>Thyroid gland (option A), sublingual gland only (option C), lacrimal gland (option D), and pituitary gland (option E) are unrelated sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The salivary gland tumor classically associated with perineural invasion is:",o:["Warthin tumor","Pleomorphic adenoma","Basal cell adenoma","Oncocytoma","Adenoid cystic carcinoma"],a:4,e:"Adenoid cystic carcinoma characteristically spreads along nerves producing severe pain. Cranial neuropathies develop clinically because of extensive perineural invasion.<br><br>Despite slow growth, the tumor demonstrates aggressive local infiltration and recurrence.<br><br>Warthin tumor (option A), pleomorphic adenoma (option B), oncocytoma (option D), and basal cell adenoma (option C) are less neurotropic.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing superficial parotidectomy is most at risk of injury to the:",o:["Lingual nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Vagus nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Facial nerve"],a:4,e:"The facial nerve traverses parotid gland and remains the most important structure during parotidectomy. Facial asymmetry develops clinically after accidental injury.<br><br>Identification of the nerve trunk near stylomastoid foramen is surgically essential.<br><br>Lingual nerve (option A), vagus nerve (option C), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option B) are less vulnerable here.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with rapidly enlarging painful salivary gland mass and cervical nodes most likely has:",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Warthin tumor","Sialadenitis only","Ranula","Malignant salivary tumor"],a:4,e:"Rapid growth, pain, and cervical lymphadenopathy strongly suggest malignant salivary gland disease. Facial nerve weakness develops clinically in advanced invasive lesions.<br><br>Benign tumors usually enlarge slowly without nodal metastasis or pain.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (option A), Warthin tumor (option B), ranula (option D), and uncomplicated sialadenitis (option C) are less aggressive conditions.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common site of pleomorphic adenoma is the:",o:["Sublingual gland","Minor salivary glands","Parotid gland","Submandibular gland","Lacrimal gland"],a:2,e:"Pleomorphic adenoma most frequently involves superficial lobe of parotid gland. Slowly progressive painless swelling develops clinically in affected patients.<br><br>Although benign, longstanding tumors carry small risk of malignant transformation.<br><br>Sublingual gland (option A), minor salivary glands (option B), submandibular gland (option D), and lacrimal gland (option E) are less frequent sites.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with adenoid cystic carcinoma commonly complains of severe pain because of:",o:["Hemorrhage","Salivary obstruction","Facial edema only","Hypercalcemia","Perineural spread"],a:4,e:"Adenoid cystic carcinoma commonly invades nerves causing severe persistent pain. Cranial neuropathies develop clinically in advanced perineural extension.<br><br>This characteristic behavior contributes to local recurrence despite apparently adequate excision.<br><br>Hemorrhage (option A), salivary obstruction (option B), hypercalcemia (option D), and isolated edema (option C) are less typical causes.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops salivary leakage through surgical wound after parotidectomy. The complication is:",o:["Ranula","Salivary fistula","Branchial fistula","Thyroglossal fistula","Tracheoesophageal fistula"],a:1,e:"Salivary fistula may follow parotid surgery because of ductal or glandular leakage. Persistent watery discharge develops clinically especially during eating.<br><br>Most fistulas resolve with pressure dressings and reduction of salivary secretion.<br><br>Ranula (option A), branchial fistula (option C), thyroglossal fistula (option D), and tracheoesophageal fistula (option E) are unrelated conditions.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A hard fixed submandibular gland mass with cervical nodes should be considered:",o:["Benign adenoma","Chronic sialadenitis only","Ranula","Viral infection only","Malignant until proven otherwise"],a:4,e:"Hard fixed salivary gland masses associated with cervical lymphadenopathy strongly suggest malignancy. Pain and nerve involvement develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Submandibular gland tumors show higher malignant potential compared with parotid tumors.<br><br>Benign adenoma (option A), chronic sialadenitis (option B), viral infection (option D), and ranula (option C) are less concerning diagnoses.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with malignant parotid tumor requires sacrifice of facial nerve during surgery. Postoperative management may include:",o:["Facial nerve grafting","Cochlear implantation","Tympanoplasty","Mastoidectomy only","Thyroid suppression therapy"],a:0,e:"Facial nerve grafting may help restore partial facial function after oncological nerve sacrifice. Facial paralysis develops clinically immediately following radical surgery.<br><br>Greater auricular or sural nerve grafts are commonly used reconstructive options.<br><br>Cochlear implantation (option B), tympanoplasty (option C), mastoidectomy (option D), and thyroid suppression (option E) are unrelated procedures.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most useful for preoperative diagnosis of salivary gland tumor is:",o:["FNAC","Barium swallow","Pure tone audiometry","Bronchoscopy","Tympanometry"],a:0,e:"FNAC provides valuable cytological diagnosis in salivary gland masses before definitive surgery. Painless gland enlargement develops clinically in most benign neoplasms.<br><br>The investigation is minimally invasive and guides surgical planning effectively.<br><br>Barium swallow (option B), audiometry (option C), bronchoscopy (option D), and tympanometry (option E) are unrelated investigations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent pleomorphic adenoma most likely had previous:",o:["Radical neck dissection","Chemotherapy only","Radiation fibrosis","Facial nerve grafting","Incomplete excision"],a:4,e:"Pleomorphic adenoma commonly recurs after incomplete excision or tumor spillage. Multiple nodules develop clinically years after inadequate surgery.<br><br>Microscopic pseudopod extensions beyond capsule predispose to recurrence if enucleation alone is performed.<br><br>Radical neck dissection (option A), radiation fibrosis (option C), facial grafting (option D), and chemotherapy (option B) are less relevant causes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The salivary gland tumor with highest likelihood of malignancy is found in the:",o:["Parotid gland","Submandibular gland","Accessory parotid tissue","Minor salivary glands","Sublingual gland"],a:4,e:"Sublingual gland tumors are uncommon but have very high malignant potential. Rapidly enlarging floor-of-mouth swelling develops clinically in affected patients.<br><br>Smaller salivary glands generally show greater probability of malignancy compared with larger glands.<br><br>Parotid gland (option A), submandibular gland (option B), minor glands (option D), and accessory parotid tissue (option C) are comparatively less malignant overall.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with low-grade mucoepidermoid carcinoma of parotid gland is most appropriately treated by:",o:["Observation only","Chemotherapy alone","Surgical excision with clear margins","Radiation only","Steroids and antibiotics"],a:2,e:"Low-grade mucoepidermoid carcinoma is primarily managed surgically with adequate excision margins. Local recurrence develops clinically after incomplete tumor clearance.<br><br>Facial nerve preservation is attempted unless direct neural invasion exists.<br><br>Observation (option A), chemotherapy alone (option B), radiation alone (option D), and steroids with antibiotics (option E) are insufficient definitive treatments.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 48-year-old man presents with slowly progressive parotid swelling and severe lancinating facial pain radiating toward temporal region. MRI demonstrates skull base extension along cranial nerves. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Warthin tumor","Mucoepidermoid carcinoma","Adenoid cystic carcinoma","Oncocytoma"],a:3,e:"Adenoid cystic carcinoma is notorious for extensive perineural spread and delayed skull base extension. Severe neuralgic pain develops clinically despite relatively slow tumor enlargement.<br><br>The tumor frequently tracks along cranial nerves, causing recurrent disease even after aggressive treatment.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (option A), Warthin tumor (option B), mucoepidermoid carcinoma (option C), and oncocytoma (option E) show less marked neurotropism.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoes total parotidectomy with facial nerve preservation for high-grade mucoepidermoid carcinoma. Postoperative radiotherapy is mainly indicated because of:",o:["Excess salivation","High local recurrence risk","Prevention of Frey syndrome","Reduction of xerostomia","Improved taste sensation"],a:1,e:"High-grade salivary malignancies demonstrate significant risk of microscopic residual disease and recurrence. Local infiltration develops clinically beyond obvious tumor margins.<br><br>Postoperative radiotherapy improves locoregional disease control after definitive surgical excision.<br><br>Excess salivation (option A), Frey syndrome prevention (option C), xerostomia reduction (option D), and taste improvement (option E) are incorrect indications.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 63-year-old smoker has bilateral parotid tail masses. Histology reveals papillary oncocytic epithelium with lymphoid stroma. The tumor is uniquely associated with:",o:["Alcohol abuse","Epstein-Barr virus","Facial trauma","Hyperthyroidism","Cigarette smoking"],a:4,e:"Warthin tumor demonstrates a strong association with cigarette smoking and may occur bilaterally. Slow painless cystic swelling develops clinically in older males predominantly.<br><br>The tumor arises almost exclusively within parotid gland tissue.<br><br>Alcohol abuse (option A), Epstein-Barr virus (option B), hyperthyroidism (option D), and facial trauma (option C) show weaker associations.<br><br><em>(Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
  {q:"During radical parotidectomy for advanced carcinoma, preservation of facial nerve is contraindicated when:",o:["Tumor size exceeds 2 cm","Cervical lymph nodes are palpable","Histology suggests low-grade lesion","Facial nerve is infiltrated by tumor","Patient is elderly"],a:3,e:"Facial nerve preservation is contraindicated when direct tumor infiltration exists intraoperatively. Progressive facial weakness develops clinically before surgery in many advanced malignant cases.<br><br>Oncological clearance takes precedence over functional preservation in invasive disease.<br><br>Tumor size alone (option A), cervical nodes (option B), low-grade histology (option C), and advanced age (option E) are insufficient indications for sacrifice.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A recurrent multinodular parotid mass appears years after enucleation of pleomorphic adenoma. The underlying pathological explanation is:",o:["Lymphatic metastasis","Radiation-induced change","Perineural dissemination","Viral transformation","Multifocal pseudopod extensions"],a:4,e:"Pleomorphic adenoma possesses microscopic pseudopod extensions beyond its capsule. Multiple recurrent nodules develop clinically after incomplete excision or capsular rupture.<br><br>Simple enucleation leaves microscopic tumor deposits behind within surrounding gland tissue.<br><br>Lymphatic metastasis (option A), radiation changes (option B), viral transformation (option D), and perineural spread (option C) are less relevant mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with parotid carcinoma develops numbness over lower auricle after surgery. The nerve most likely sacrificed intentionally during flap elevation was:",o:["Lingual nerve","Great auricular nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Lesser occipital nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:1,e:"Great auricular nerve commonly traverses operative field during parotidectomy and may require sacrifice. Sensory loss develops clinically over ear lobule and mandibular angle.<br><br>The nerve arises from cervical plexus and provides cutaneous sensation around parotid region.<br><br>Lingual nerve (option A), glossopharyngeal nerve (option C), lesser occipital nerve (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option E) have different distributions.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with minor salivary gland tumor of palate presents with ulceration, fixation, and bone erosion. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Pleomorphic adenoma","Warthin tumor","Low-grade adenoma","Mucocele","Malignant salivary neoplasm"],a:4,e:"Ulceration, fixation, and palatal bone destruction strongly suggest malignant salivary gland disease. Pain and local invasion develop clinically in advanced lesions.<br><br>Minor salivary gland tumors possess higher probability of malignancy than parotid lesions.<br><br>Pleomorphic adenoma (option A), Warthin tumor (option B), low-grade adenoma (option C), and mucocele (option D) are less destructive.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops immediate complete facial paralysis after superficial parotidectomy despite anatomically intact nerve. The most likely explanation is:",o:["Lingual nerve edema","Hematogenous metastasis","Neuropraxia from traction injury","Chorda tympani syndrome","Thoracic outlet compression"],a:2,e:"Temporary facial paralysis may occur after excessive manipulation or traction of facial nerve during surgery. Weakness develops clinically immediately after operative recovery.<br><br>Most neuropraxic injuries improve gradually over weeks to months.<br><br>Lingual nerve edema (option A), metastasis (option B), chorda tympani syndrome (option D), and thoracic outlet compression (option E) are unrelated causes.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A high-grade parotid malignancy with clinically positive cervical lymph nodes most appropriately requires:",o:["Observation alone","Superficial parotidectomy only","Needle aspiration only","Parotidectomy with neck dissection","Steroid therapy alone"],a:3,e:"Clinically positive cervical lymphadenopathy indicates regional metastatic disease requiring neck dissection. Pain and facial weakness develop clinically in advanced aggressive tumors.<br><br>Combined surgery improves regional disease control and staging accuracy.<br><br>Observation (option A), superficial parotidectomy alone (option B), aspiration only (option C), and steroids (option E) are inadequate management strategies.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with long-standing pleomorphic adenoma suddenly develops rapid enlargement, pain, and facial weakness. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Warthin tumor transformation","Acute sialadenitis","Carcinoma ex pleomorphic adenoma","Mucocele formation","Benign oncocytoma"],a:2,e:"Malignant transformation of pleomorphic adenoma should be suspected after sudden rapid enlargement and facial nerve involvement. Pain and fixation develop clinically in invasive disease.<br><br>Long-standing untreated pleomorphic adenomas carry risk of malignant degeneration over time.<br><br>Warthin transformation (option A), acute sialadenitis (option B), mucocele formation (option D), and benign oncocytoma (option E) are less likely explanations.<br><br><em>(Recall and Robbins Basic Pathology)</em>"},
];